= Export Maya geoCache =

"""Exports Houdini point geometry as a Maya geometry cache (.xml + .mc files)."""

== Overview ==

This node bakes a Houdini geometry sequence into the Maya geometry cache
format (one `.mc` file per frame plus an `.xml` descriptor). The resulting
files can be loaded in Maya via __Cache > Geometry Cache > Attach Existing
Cache__ on a mesh shape node.

Each Houdini **point group** on the input geometry becomes one channel in the
cache.  The group name must match the Maya shape node name for Maya to map the
channel back to the correct mesh.

== Point Group and Maya Node Naming ==

Maya's geometry cache system identifies which mesh a channel belongs to by
matching the channel name against the mesh **shape node name**.

:tip:
    In Maya's Outliner (with __Shapes__ visible), note the exact name of the
    shape node you want to drive — for example `pSphereShape1`.  Create a
    Houdini point group with that exact name on the points that correspond to
    that mesh's vertices.

Example:

table>>
    tr>>
        th>> Houdini point group
        th>> Maya shape node it drives
    tr>>
        td>> `pSphereShape1`
        td>> `pSphereShape1`
    tr>>
        td>> `bodyMeshShape`
        td>> `bodyMeshShape`

The vertex count and order in the point group must exactly match the Maya
mesh — Maya does not perform any matching by position.

== Source Geometry Requirements ==

This HDA reads geometry per-frame using `geometryAtFrame()` and does **not**
step the global frame counter.  A live DOP simulation connected directly to
the input will produce incorrect results because the DOP network requires
sequential frame cooking to accumulate simulation state.

**Always bake your geometry simulation to a cache (e.g. File Cache SOP or
bgeo sequence) before connecting it to this HDA.**

== Parameters ==

Start Frame:
    First frame to cache.

End Frame:
    Last frame to cache (inclusive).

Evaluation Rate:
    Fraction of a frame between successive cache samples.  `1` = one sample
    per frame.  `0.5` = two samples per frame (sub-frame caching).

XML:
    Full path to the output `.xml` descriptor file, including filename and
    extension.  The per-frame `.mc` files are written to the same directory
    with the pattern `<base>Frame<N>.mc`.

Cache:
    Click to start the export.  A progress dialog allows cancellation.

Python Module Path:
    Path to `nCache.py`.  Required at runtime; the HDA loads the module from
    this path each time __Cache__ is pressed.

== How to Attach the Cache in Maya ==

# Select the mesh object(s) whose shape names match your point group names.
# In Maya, go to __Cache > Geometry Cache > Attach Existing Cache__.
# Select the `.xml` file exported by this HDA.
# Maya reads the XML, matches each channel to the corresponding shape by
  name, and wires up the cache connections automatically.

:note:
    If you use __File > Import__ instead of __Attach Existing Cache__, Maya
    will not set up the geometry cache connections.
